               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410614-name-1295" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410614-name-1295" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410614-name-1295" type="surname" value="WHITE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410614-name-1295" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY WHITE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of John Horne, of St. Margaret's-hill, High-street, Borough. These handkerchiefs were on a pile of goods on the night of the 20th of May—I saw them safe about half-past eight or nine o'clock—between nine and ten I went to the door and found the prisoners in custody—I then missed the handkerchiefs—these are them—they have our mark on them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410614-name-1296" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410614-name-1296" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410614-name-1296" type="surname" value="LANK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410614-name-1296" type="given" value="CORNELIUS"></interp>CORNELIUS LANK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 144.) On the 20th of May I saw the prisoners near Mr. Home's—I saw Overy come from the door three or four yards to the front of the window and pass this piece of handkerchief to Davis—I ran across the road and secured them both—they resisted all they could, and Davis threw the handkerchiefs down after I took him —I had not seen them in company before I saw Overy with the hand<lb></lb>kerchiefs—they went at once to the shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Davis's Defence.</hi> Overy picked the handkerchiefs up and passed them to me, and the policeman came and took me.</p>
